observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct the:

The Municipal Accountant to:

i.	verify the CIP accounts as to its completion and validate with the records of the Municipal Engineer;

ii.	prepare a comprehensive lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation expense and the accumulated depreciation for each class of PPE, incorporating therein the correct residual value of 5%;

iii.	prepare the Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to correct the misclassification of PPE to another account;

iv.	initiate the transfer of completed public infrastructure assets in the Trust Fund to the General Fund duly supporting with subsidiary ledgers;

v.	prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account;

b. The General Service Officer to prepare and maintain property cards for all PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office;

c. The Municipal Engineer to validate the records of the Municipal Accountant pertaining to the CIP accounts maintained for years; and

d. The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory- taking activities, conduct and complete the physical inventory in three months or less and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the SLCs; 

 require the General Services/Supply Office to keep and maintain SCs; 

order the physical count of inventories and to prepare and submit the RPCI;

We recommended that Management:

a. Implement immediately and on a timely basis the identified PPAs under the 20 percent DF. Require the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and other concerned officers to monitor the implementation of the projects to fast tract its completion and for the constituents to enjoy the benefits that may be derived therefrom;

b. Include the specific details of PPAs to be charged from 20 percent DF in the Municipality’s Annual Investment Plan (AIP) and Annual Budget and avoid lump sum appropriation;

c. Ensure that guidelines/criteria are set prior to the grant of loan assistance to indigent constituents; and

d. Direct the concerned officials/officers to monitor repayment of loans by sending demand letters to the Loan Beneficiaries.

We recommended that Management:

a. Exercise prudence in the utilization of its LDRRMF, taking into consideration the existing rules and regulations governing the utilization of the said fund and require the MDRRMO and Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds for the administrative expenses chargeable against MOOE of the MDRRM Office;

b. Ensure that the whole LDRRMF including STF and all PPAs charged against the LDRRMF are incorporated to and covered by the Municipality’s LDRRMFIP;

c. Refrain from charging against LDRRMF those expenditures not pertaining to DRRM or not in accordance with the primary purpose for which the fund was established, otherwise, these transactions shall be disallowed in audit; and

d. Submit explanation/justification on the noted deficiencies.

We recommended that Management require the LSB to:

a. Formulate and issue budget prioritization policies and tentative budget ceilings for the Municipality thru a Budget Call within the prescribed period;

b. Observe the timely preparation and approval of the SEF budget as prescribed in the JC. This allows prompt submission to relevant offices, providing them with adequate time for review, consolidation and evaluation of the reports, and ultimately enhancing transparency and accountability;

c. Regularly submit the quarterly and annual SEF utilization reports (SEF Budget Accountability Form No. 1) to the DepEd CO, thorough appropriate channels, copy furnished the Regional Offices of the DBM and DILG; and

d. Ensure that the SEF utilization reports are regularly posted in the LGU website quarterly and must not be later than the 20th day after the end of each quarter as required by the Revised Implementing Guidelines on Full Disclosure Policy pursuant to DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2024-021.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct the:
GAD Focal Person to:
Ensure that all program activities are supported by complete and verifiable documentation, including distribution list;
Ensure that all identified PPAs in the GAD Plan and Budget are fully implemented and that GAD Fund is optimally utilized, amounting to at least 5% of the total municipal budget, through proper planning and timely execution of PPAs as outlined in the GPB and;
Ensure timely posting of GAD AR to FDPP in accordance with JMC 2013-01, to uphold transparency and compliance with national reporting requirements; and
The Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking Disbursement Vouchers along with the supporting documents to the Audit Team to validate reported expenditures and ensure the integrity and accuracy of financial records related to GAD implementation.

We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct: 

a.	The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries in the Cash in Local Treasury account and reflect such adjustments to the affected Financial Statements, and ensure accuracy in the recording of collections and deposits as incorporated in the Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD);

b.	The Municipal Treasurer to submit the RCD to the Municipal Accountant within 10 days following the end of each reporting month;

c.	The Municipal Treasurer to submit the complete Bank Statement for all bank accounts to the Municipal Accountant for the proper verification of all deposits made; and

d.	Implement frequent reconciliation of records between the accounting and the treasurer’s office.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct:

a. the LDRRM Officer to include the available fund totaling to ₱1,618,229.73 in the LDRRMFIP by incorporating responsive and beneficial local disaster risk reduction and management related PPAs and the budget for each PPA should be specified as to the year of unutilized balance it will be charged and not in lumpsum; and

b. the Municipal Accountant to prepare the correct and complete LDRRMF Utilization Report duly validated and reconciled with the records of the Office of the Municipal Treasurer and the Office of the Municipal Budget Officer and be submitted to the audit team within the reglementary period and the same be posted in the DILG’s Full Disclosure Policy Portal;

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

 (a)  require all collectors to prepare and submit the RAAF incorporating therein the received, issued and cancelled accountable forms with and without face value; 

(b)  submit all obsolete bank checks accompanied by inventory reports; 

(c) ensure that all collections made are duly acknowledged by issuing the appropriate accountable forms; and 

(d) impose internal control measures for the immediate remittance of collections.

Prepare and issue a well-defined set of policies and local guidelines governing the implementation of AICS program which must be aligned with the guidelines issued by the DSWD governing the grants of AICS. The policies and guidelines must contain the following:

•	Kind of financial assistance (burial, transportation, medical, educational, food, shelter and others);

•	Limitations on the amounts given per kind of financial assistance;

•	Criteria in granting the financial assistance and the documentary requirements for each particular case; and

•	Well defined roles and responsibilities of the officials processing requests.

Strictly observe the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 and its applicable IRR, such that all procurements must be conducted through public bidding. Alternative methods of procurement must be resorted to only in highly exceptional cases provided for in RA No. 9184;

Require the BAC to supervise all types of procurement, not just infrastructure projects but also goods, pursuant to Section 11.1 of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A No. 9184;

Discontinue procurement through reimbursement basis unless extremely urgent, necessary and in small amount; and

Ensure that an APP is prepared to support the Annual Budget of the LGU which must incorporate all its procurement requirements for each calendar year, to avoid audit disallowance thereof.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to immediately release the unremitted shares of the Province and Barangays out of its collections from real property and special education taxes. Regular monitoring and coordination with the concerned LGUs must be observed to avoid accumulation of the balances. Moreover, records for the share of specific Barangay in RPT collections must be maintained so that remittance to the latter will be expediently facilitated;

Require the Municipal Accountant to come up with a reconciliation of the variance between the balance of RPT and SET Receivables;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the SLCs; 



 require the General Services/Supply Office to keep and maintain SCs; 



order the physical count of inventories and to prepare and submit the RPCI;

We reiterated our recommendations that the LCE:
Prioritize issuance of demand letter to all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate/settle their outstanding cash advances;
Require the Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding cash advances and conduct verification, analysis and validation of them to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted; and
Conform with the procedures and requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and immediately facilitate the request for write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advances.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of inventory count of all the local roads and prepare and submit the RPCLRN;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain separate SLs/LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, for local road projects and reconcile both records to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the RLRN and Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road network and provide proper and complete disclosure of the total road networks in the Notes to FS in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that Management strictly comply with DILG, DOF and DBM JMC No. 1, as follows:
Maximize the utilization of the 20 percent DF and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the social, economic and environmental outcomes essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all;
Define completely in the Annual Investment Plan (AIP) and in the Annual Budget the specific PPAs to be funded by the 20 percent DF, discontinue the practice of lump sum budgeting and create guidelines/criteria on the grant of assistance/livelihood program;
Ensure the completeness and accuracy of the reports produced, particularly the implementation of PPAs whether funded by current or continuing appropriations to provide relevant information to decision makers; and
Formulate well-defined procedures to enhance the monitoring and evaluation activities during project implementation, which includes among others, the coordination with the Municipal Engineer in monitoring the implementation of projects funded from the 20 percent DF to attain the optimal socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes which is the core of the fund allocation.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the trial balances, together with all the supporting financial/accounting reports, within the prescribed period to facilitate the review and analysis of the accounts appearing in the financial reports and to affirm the reliability of Management’s assertions;
Consider hiring additional competent staffs and personnel in the Accounting Office to hasten the process of preparation and submission of monthly, quarterly and annual financial reports to the Office of the Auditor;
Direct the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Budget Officer to be mindful of the deadlines and adhere with the provisions of Sections 70 and 73 of NGAS Manual for LGUs, specifically on the submission of trial balances, FS, SAAOB and other supporting schedules; and
Evaluate the process of preparing the reports and relevant documents in the Accounting, Treasury and Budget Offices and come up with procedures/methods to cope up with the submission of financial reports to COA. Constantly remind the Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Offices within the LGU to submit the pending reports/documents to the Municipal Accountant in order to avoid delay in the preparation and submission of financial reports to COA.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the LSB to refrain from expending funds without an approved SEF Budget. Likewise, direct the Municipal Budget Officer to properly monitor the existence of available appropriation of each ObR to prevent any illegal disbursement of funds;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that proper accounts are used in the recording of the financial transactions and supporting documents thereof are complete. Further, make necessary adjusting entries to correct the affected FS accounts; 
Submit a satisfactory explanation on the deficiencies noted as well as the lacking supporting documents; and
Direct the LSB to ensure that prescribed planning and budgeting tools are effectively utilized and the timelines in the planning and budgeting process are strictly observed as prescribed under DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017.

We recommended that the LCE, through the Municipal Ecological Solid Waste Management Board:
Include in the Municipal’s AIP the PPAs listed in the 10-year SWM Plan and prepare and submit to the Audit Team the accomplishment thereof as of year-end;
Strictly enforce and intensify the information campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy among residents and consider imposing fines and penalties for violators thereof;
Re-establish the MRF of the concerned Barangay and require from its officials and constituents, strict compliance to the guidelines and criteria set under RA No. 9003;
Allocate funds for the construction and operation of a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes; and
Hasten the implementation of all SWM related PPAs to enforce proper sorting, segregation, composting, recycling and disposal of waste materials to efficiently address solid wastes concerns within the Municipality.
Furthermore, we recommended that LCE ensure that charges to government funds are appropriate and supporting documents therewith are valid, proper and legal and that the Municipal Budget Officer also ensure that ObR are deducted from appropriate funds based on Municipal’s Approved Annual Budget. Moreover, Management direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure the completeness of required supporting documents of each financial transaction prior to any disbursement of funds.

We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct:
The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries in the Cash in Local Treasury account and reflect such adjustments to the affected Financial Statements, and ensure accuracy in the recording of collections and deposits as incorporated in the Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD);
The Acting Municipal Treasurer to submit the RCD to the Municipal Accountant within 10 days following the end of each reporting month;
The Acting Municipal Treasurer to submit the complete Bank Statement for all bank accounts to the Municipal Accountant for the proper verification of all deposits made; and
Implement frequent reconciliation of records between the accounting and the treasurer’s office.
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer have acknowledged the audit observations and promised to act on the recommendations provided by the Audit Team.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct the:
Municipal Accountant to:
clearly identify the reconciling items in the BRS for the seven bank accounts and draw the necessary JEV to recognize all reconciling items that require adjustments and correction in the books of accounts;
immediately prepare and submit the BRS for the remaining five bank accounts, take up reconciling items, and prepare necessary adjusting journal entries;
regularly submit the mandatory financial reports and the supporting documents within the reglementary period;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to post the balances of the Cash in Bank- LCCA in the cashbook, with proper segregation of the sources of funds; and coordinate with the depository bank to ensure the prompt delivery of the monthly bank statements or its equivalent to facilitate the timely reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts; and
Provide the Accounting Unit with accounting proficient support staff to ensure that mandatory financial reports are submitted within the reglementary period.
The Municipal Accountant was able to submit the remaining BRS however, the reported Cash in Bank- LCCA was not adjusted to conform to the balances based on the BRS.  Also, errors where not specifically identified as to the particular transaction it pertains.
During the exit conference, the Municipal Accountant promised to prepare and submit a comprehensive BRS duly supported with complete bank statement for all bank accounts maintained by the Municipality.
The Audit Team will closely monitor the compliance of the Municipal Accountant since the same audit observation has been noted by the team referencing to AAR CYs 2021-2, 2019-2, and 2018-1.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct the:
The Municipal Accountant to:
verify the CIP accounts as to its completion and validate with the records of the Municipal Engineer;
prepare a comprehensive lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation expense and the accumulated depreciation for each class of PPE, incorporating therein the correct residual value of 5%;
prepare the Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to correct the misclassification of PPE to another account;
initiate the transfer of completed public infrastructure assets in the Trust Fund to the General Fund duly supporting with subsidiary ledgers;
prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account;
The General Service Officer to prepare and maintain property cards for all PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office;
The Municipal Engineer to validate the records of the Municipal Accountant pertaining to the CIP accounts maintained for years; and
The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory- taking activities, conduct and complete the physical inventory in three months or less and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.
The department heads concerned, during the exit conference on April 18, 2024 promised to comply with the audit recommendations.
The Audit Team will closely monitor the compliance of the Municipality on these audit recommendations as these are reiteration of the calendar year’s 2022-3, 2021-3, 2021-7, and 2019-4 audit recommendations which remained unimplemented to date.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct:
The department heads concerned to fast track the completion/acquisition of the development projects, and moving forward, to ensure that all development projects are completed as of yearend;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare the quarterly reports on the utilization of the 20% DF duly validated by the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Budget Officer and submit the same to oversight agencies;
The Municipal Monitoring Team to ensure that all development projects are used as intended so that optimum socio-economic benefits are attained and enjoyed by the target beneficiaries.
The Municipal Engineer and the BAC Chairperson have acknowledged the audit observation and promised the Audit Team its prompt actions in implementing the audit recommendations.
Further, the Municipal Engineer, the Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant promised their proper coordination in order to submit accurate and uniform reports to oversight agencies.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Agriculturist to:
• put into writing the change in the agreement as regards payment schedule to protect the interest of the Municipality and ensure collectability of the amount of P51,000.00 from farmer-beneficiaries due at the planting time;
• continue to monitor and evaluate the results/accomplishments of the program and submit results/Monitoring and Evaluation Reports of the program as required in the design of the project;
• continue to monitor the collection of the fifty percent of the price per seedlings due for payment at planting time;
• inform the farmer-beneficiaries to conduct continuous field monitoring for pest control and report to PCA and the Municipal Agriculturist immediately for any pest/diseases in the coconut; and
• instruct the farmer-beneficiaries to refrain from taking actions not in accordance with the provisions of the written Memorandum of Agreement.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Disaster and Risk Reduction Management Officer to prepare the:
• Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances for In-kind Donations;
• Report on the Receipt and Utilization of Cash Donations;
• Report on the Receipt and Distribution/Issuance of Donated Relief Goods; and
• Report on the Receipt and Distribution/Issuance of Donated PPE; and furnish the same to the NDRRMC, through the OCD, copy furnished the Audit Team within 10 working days after the end of each quarter pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Agriculturist to:
• put into writing the change in the agreement as regards payment schedule to protect the interest of the Municipality and ensure collectability of the amount of P98,500.00 from farmer-beneficiaries due at the planting time;
• continue to monitor and evaluate the results/accomplishments of the program and submit Monitoring and Evaluation Reports as required in the design of the project;
• continue to monitor the collection of the fifty percent of the price per seedlings due for payment at planting time; and
• instruct the farmer-beneficiaries to monitor their respective farm and report to PCA and the Municipal Agriculturist immediately for any pest/diseases in the coconut.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Agriculturist to:
 put into writing the change in the agreement as regards payment schedule to protect the interest of the Municipality and ensure collectability of the amount of P95,000.00 from farmer beneficiaries due at the planting time;
 continue to monitor and evaluate the results/accomplishments of the program and submit Monitoring and Evaluation Reports as required in the design of the project;
 continue to monitor the collection of the fifty percent of the price per seedlings due for payment at planting time; and
 the farmer beneficiaries to monitor their respective farm and report to PCA and the Municipal Agriculturist immeditely for any pest/diseases in the coconut.
